# Guide to Testing in Spring Boot

Testing is a fantastic way to ensure your code works exactly as you expect and doesn't break when you make changes later! In a Spring Boot app like DevPulse, we generally write two types of tests: **Unit Tests** and **Integration Tests**.

---

## 1. The Basics: What are we testing?

- **Unit Tests (`@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)`)**: We test a *single* class in isolation. For example, testing [UserServiceImpl](file:///c:/Users/vamsh/.sping/DevPulse/src/main/java/com/example/user/service/UserServiceImpl.java#15-64). Since it depends on [UserRepository](file:///C:/Users/vamsh/.sping/DevPulse/src/main/java/com/example/user/repository/UserRepository.java#10-18), we "mock" (fake) the repository so we aren't actually calling the database. This makes tests extremely fast.
- **Integration Tests (`@SpringBootTest`, `@DataJpaTest`, or `@WebMvcTest`)**: We test how multiple parts of the application work *together*. For example, testing the [UserController](file:///C:/Users/vamsh/.sping/DevPulse/src/main/java/com/example/user/controller/UserController.java#16-46) all the way down to the database to ensure the whole flow works.

Let's start with Unit Tests, as they are the easiest to write and run!

---

## 2. Setting Up Your First Unit Test

Let's write a unit test for your [IdeaServiceImpl](file:///C:/Users/vamsh/.sping/DevPulse/src/main/java/com/example/idea/service/IdeaServiceImpl.java#20-175)! We want to test the [getIdeaById](file:///C:/Users/vamsh/.sping/DevPulse/src/main/java/com/example/idea/service/IdeaServiceImpl.java#80-98) method to ensure it correctly fetches an idea, and correctly throws an exception if the idea doesn't exist.

### Step 1: Create the Test File
You have your main code in [src/main/java/com/example/idea/service/IdeaServiceImpl.java](file:///C:/Users/vamsh/.sping/DevPulse/src/main/java/com/example/idea/service/IdeaServiceImpl.java).
Your tests should mirror this structure in the `test` directory! 

Create this file: `src/test/java/com/example/idea/service/IdeaServiceImplTest.java`

### Step 2: The Basic Structure

Here is how you set up a test file using Mockito (a library that creates "fake" objects):

```java
package com.example.idea.service;

import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.*; // For checking results
import static org.mockito.Mockito.*; // For mocking

import java.time.LocalDateTime;
import java.util.Optional;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.extension.ExtendWith;
import org.mockito.InjectMocks;
import org.mockito.Mock;
import org.mockito.junit.jupiter.MockitoExtension;

import com.example.idea.dto.IdeaResponse;
import com.example.idea.entity.Idea;
import com.example.idea.exception.IdeaNotFoundByIDException;
import com.example.idea.repository.IdeaRepository;
import com.example.user.entity.User;

// 1. Tell JUnit to use Mockito to handle our fake objects
@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class) 
class IdeaServiceImplTest {

    // 2. Create FAKE versions of the dependencies IdeaServiceImpl needs
    @Mock
    private IdeaRepository ideaRepo;

    // 3. Inject the fake objects into the REAL service we want to test
    @InjectMocks
    private IdeaServiceImpl ideaService;

    // We will put our tests here!
}
```

---

## 3. Writing Your First Test: The "Happy Path"

Let's test the scenario where the idea *is* found successfully. Every good test follows a pattern called **Arrange, Act, Assert (AAA)**.

Add this method inside `IdeaServiceImplTest`:

```java
    @Test
    void getIdeaById_WhenIdeaExists_ShouldReturnIdeaResponse() {
        // --- ARRANGE ---
        // 1. Prepare fake data
        Long ideaId = 1L;
        User fakeUser = new User();
        fakeUser.setEmail("test@example.com");

        Idea fakeIdea = new Idea();
        fakeIdea.setId(ideaId);
        fakeIdea.setTitle("Test Title");
        fakeIdea.setCreatedBy(fakeUser);
        fakeIdea.setCreatedAt(LocalDateTime.now());

        // 2. Tell our fake repository what to do!
        // "When someone asks for an idea with ID 1, return this fakeIdea"
        when(ideaRepo.findById(ideaId)).thenReturn(Optional.of(fakeIdea));

        // --- ACT ---
        // Run the actual method we are testing
        IdeaResponse result = ideaService.getIdeaById(ideaId);

        // --- ASSERT ---
        // Check if the result was what we expected
        assertNotNull(result); // Result shouldn't be null
        assertEquals(ideaId, result.getId()); // ID should match
        assertEquals("Test Title", result.getTitle()); // Title should match
        assertEquals("test@example.com", result.getCreatedBy()); // Email should match
    }
```

---

## 4. Writing Your Second Test: The "Unhappy Path"

What if the idea doesn't exist? [IdeaServiceImpl](file:///C:/Users/vamsh/.sping/DevPulse/src/main/java/com/example/idea/service/IdeaServiceImpl.java#20-175) is supposed to throw [IdeaNotFoundByIDException](file:///C:/Users/vamsh/.sping/DevPulse/src/main/java/com/example/idea/exception/IdeaNotFoundByIDException.java#6-17). Let's test that!

Add this second method to your test class:

```java
    @Test
    void getIdeaById_WhenIdeaDoesNotExist_ShouldThrowException() {
        // --- ARRANGE ---
        Long ideaId = 99L;
        // Tell the fake repository to return empty (not found)
        when(ideaRepo.findById(ideaId)).thenReturn(Optional.empty());

        // --- ACT & ASSERT ---
        // Check that calling the method throws the exact exception we expect
        assertThrows(IdeaNotFoundByIDException.class, () -> {
            ideaService.getIdeaById(ideaId);
        });
    }
```

---

