## 5. Testing a Controller (Web Layer)

Testing controllers is slightly different. Instead of just calling a method, we want to simulate a real HTTP request (like a POST or GET) hitting your endpoint. 

Spring provides `@WebMvcTest` and `MockMvc` for this. This tests the web layer without starting the full server, while still mocking the service layer.

Let's test the `UserController.register` endpoint. Create `src/test/java/com/example/user/controller/UserControllerTest.java`:

```java
package com.example.user.controller;

import static org.mockito.ArgumentMatchers.any;
import static org.mockito.Mockito.doNothing;
import static org.springframework.test.web.servlet.request.MockMvcRequestBuilders.post;
import static org.springframework.test.web.servlet.result.MockMvcResultMatchers.content;
import static org.springframework.test.web.servlet.result.MockMvcResultMatchers.status;

import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.springframework.beans.factory.annotation.Autowired;
import org.springframework.boot.test.autoconfigure.web.servlet.AutoConfigureMockMvc;
import org.springframework.boot.test.autoconfigure.web.servlet.WebMvcTest;
import org.springframework.boot.test.mock.mockito.MockBean;
import org.springframework.http.MediaType;
import org.springframework.test.web.servlet.MockMvc;

import com.example.user.dto.RegisterRequest;
import com.example.user.service.UserService;
import com.fasterxml.jackson.databind.ObjectMapper;

// 1. Tell Spring to only load the web layer for UserController
@WebMvcTest(UserController.class)
@AutoConfigureMockMvc(addFilters = false) // Disable security filters for this simple test
class UserControllerTest {

    // 2. MockMvc allows us to send fake HTTP requests
    @Autowired
    private MockMvc mockMvc;

    // 3. We mock the service layer because we are only testing the controller
    @MockBean
    private UserService userService;

    // 4. ObjectMapper converts Java objects to JSON
    @Autowired
    private ObjectMapper objectMapper;

    @Test
    void register_WithValidRequest_ShouldReturnCreated() throws Exception {
        // --- ARRANGE ---
        RegisterRequest request = new RegisterRequest();
        request.setName("Test User");
        request.setEmail("test@email.com");
        request.setPassword("P@ssword123");

        // The register method returns void, so we tell Mockito to "do nothing" when it's called
        doNothing().when(userService).register(any(RegisterRequest.class));

        // --- ACT & ASSERT ---
        // Perform a POST request to /api/users/register
        mockMvc.perform(post("/api/users/register")
                .contentType(MediaType.APPLICATION_JSON) // We are sending JSON
                .content(objectMapper.writeValueAsString(request))) // Convert our Java object to JSON string
                
                // Assert the HTTP status is 201 CREATED
                .andExpect(status().isCreated())
                
                // Assert the response body contains our success message
                .andExpect(content().string("User registered successfully."));
    }
}
```

### Key Differences for Controllers:
1. We use **`@WebMvcTest`** and **`@MockBean`** instead of `@ExtendWith(MockitoExtension.class)` and `@Mock`. This is because we need Spring to partially boot up to handle the HTTP stuff.
2. We use **`MockMvc`** to simulate the user making a request (POST, GET, etc.).
3. We use **`.andExpect()`** to assert the HTTP status code and response body, rather than standard JUnit assertions like `assertEquals()`.

Now you have a complete guide! Try implementing the `IdeaServiceImplTest` first, make sure it passes, and then give the `UserControllerTest` a try!
